      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texas was a diverse region with multiple groups holding different loyalties and interests. These differences influenced the revolution’s social dynamics.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; tshaonline.org; education.texashistory.unt.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texas had Anglo-American settlers, Tejanos (Mexican Texans), indigenous peoples, and enslaved African Americans</li><li>Anglo settlers were the majority by 1835</li><li>Cultural and political differences created tensions</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Tejanos often sought to balance loyalty to Mexico with local interests.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify challenges in uniting diverse groups for a common cause.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all Texans supported independence equally.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; tshaonline.org; education.texashistory.unt.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s21\">[21]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s22\">[22]</sup></p>"
