      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The revolution was not a unified movement; differing loyalties among settlers and Tejanos influenced the course and nature of the war.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; tshaonline.org; education.texashistory.unt.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Not all Texans supported independence; some remained loyal to Mexico</li><li>Tejanos were divided between supporting Mexico and the revolution</li><li>Internal divisions complicated the conflict</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Some Tejanos fought alongside Mexican troops, while others joined Texan forces.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider reasons why people in the same region might support opposing sides.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming a single, unified Texan identity during the revolution.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; tshaonline.org; education.texashistory.unt.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s21\">[21]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s22\">[22]</sup></p>"
