    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Analyzing Letters from Texas Revolution Leaders</h2><ul><li>Letters reveal personal motivations and challenges faced by leaders</li><li>Show differing perspectives on the revolution’s progress</li><li>Highlight communication difficulties and morale issues</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Examining letters from key figures like Sam Houston and William B. Travis provides insight into the human side of the revolution, showing how leaders viewed events and made decisions under pressure. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from Travis at the Alamo expresses determination despite being outnumbered, illustrating the resolve of Texan defenders.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Read an excerpt from a leader’s letter and identify their main concerns and emotions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming letters are purely factual; they often contain bias and emotional appeals.</p></div></div>",
