      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Mexico’s loss of Texas was a significant blow to its territorial integrity and revealed internal challenges. The revolution contributed to political instability and inspired other regions to consider independence or autonomy.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Loss of Texas weakened Mexican territorial control</li><li>Exposed weaknesses in Mexican government and military</li><li>Increased internal political instability in Mexico</li><li>Set precedent for future regional separatist movements</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Following Texas independence, Mexico faced further rebellions and struggled to maintain control over northern territories.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Evaluate how the Texas Revolution influenced Mexico’s political landscape in the 1830s and beyond.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Mexico quickly recovered from the loss of Texas without lasting effects.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s21\">[21]</sup></p>"
