    "num": "30",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">30</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Application</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Analyzing Primary Sources on the Revolution’s Legacy</h2><ul><li>Examine letters and government records post-1836</li><li>Identify perspectives on Texas independence and governance</li><li>Assess biases and reliability of sources</li><li>Connect primary evidence to historical interpretations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Using primary sources from after the revolution helps understand how contemporaries viewed Texas independence and its challenges, revealing complexities beyond secondary summaries. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from Sam Houston discussing governance challenges illustrates the provisional government’s struggles.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a provided primary source excerpt and identify the author’s perspective and possible bias.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Taking primary sources at face value without considering context or bias.</p></div></div>",
