      "secnum": "Deep Dive 31",
      "h": "Governance Challenges in Revolutionary Texas",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Simulating the provisional government meeting helps learners understand the practical difficulties of governing a new republic amid internal divisions and external threats.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Role-play key figures debating governance challenges</li><li>Discuss issues like law enforcement, defense, and diplomacy</li><li>Explore differing priorities among settlers and Tejanos</li><li>Practice negotiation and decision-making skills</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Debate over how to allocate limited resources between military defense and civil administration.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>In your role, argue for your group’s priorities and seek compromise with others.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Oversimplifying the provisional government as unified and effective.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s21\">[21]</sup></p>"
