      "h": "Contextualizing Revolutionary Governance",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Comparing the Texas Revolution’s governance with other revolutions deepens understanding of common patterns and unique factors influencing revolutionary success and state-building.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Identify similarities with American and Mexican revolutions</li><li>Examine differences in political structures and challenges</li><li>Consider how context shapes revolutionary outcomes</li><li>Apply lessons from Texas to broader revolutionary studies</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Unlike the U.S. Revolution, Texas struggled with international recognition and internal divisions during its provisional government phase.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Compare governance challenges in Texas with those in another revolution you know.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all revolutions follow the same political trajectory.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s21\">[21]</sup></p>"
